body:
Unfused iterators strike again! Iterators in general cannot have `next` called on them after they return `None`. However, `FlatMap`'s `next` and `next_back` methods poll this repeatedly.

If a `FlatMap` has a non-`None` `backiter`, exhausting the iterable through `next` means calling

    match self.iter.next().map(&mut self.f) {
        None => return self.backiter.as_mut().and_then(|it| it.next()),
        ...
    }

repeatedly after `iter` was exhausted, and vice-versa if it has a `frontiter` and is exhausted backwards.

The most obvious fix is to make the `iter` field fused, though that has a performance penalty.

---

Ugly code sample:

    struct Unfused(u8, u8);

    impl Iterator for Unfused {
        type Item = u8;
        fn next(&mut self) -> Option<u8> {
            if self.0 == self.1 {
                println!("finished (next)");
                return None;
            }

            let x = self.0;
            self.0 += 1;
            Some(x)
        }
    }

    impl DoubleEndedIterator for Unfused {
        fn next_back(&mut self) -> Option<u8> {
            if self.0 == self.1 {
                println!("finished (next_back)");
                return None;
            }

            self.1 -= 1;
            Some(self.1)
        }
    }

    fn main() {
        let mut myiter = Unfused(0, 2).flat_map(|_| (0..2));
        myiter.next_back();
        for _ in myiter {}
    }

This prints `finished (next)` twice, both times from `next`.
